  "text": "and CSN3I4 are similar in Iberian/French wild and domestic populations, with the A allele always being the more common allele (Tab. I). In contrast, English wild rabbits show a higher proportion of the B allele in both CSN3I1 and CSN3I4. To the exception of this population, our results were in close agreement with those reported by Hiripi et al. [CITATION_1] for two different stocks belonging to the New Zealand White breed (Tab. I). No significant departures from Hardy-Weinberg expectations were detected in wild rabbit samples from Iberia and France, while a significant heterozygous deficit occurred in both English wild rabbits and domestic breeds (data not shown). The inclusion of related individuals in our samples together with the relatively small population size of both English wild and domestic breed populations are possible explanations for this observation.",
